  <div class="field-comment-body view-mode-full">
    <p>Hi Brian</p><p> Your points regarding limitation of Javascript APIs were helpful. Although TCPSocket support is already working for FFOS: <a href="https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/API/TCPSocket">https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/API/TCPSocket</a></p><p>Alljoyn daemon listens on tcp port, so can we do something like installing a daemon binary on the device, and use javascript to access the daemon over tcp?. It looks similar to how AJTC is implemented?. OR what about considering FFOS device as  a thin client and porting only thin client part of the code to Javascript?.  </p><p>Another point that comes to mind is, is it possible to run Alljoyn daemon behind a web service?. This way a regular javascript app would be able to access the daemon and use alljoyn service? (Is this a topic for a separate thread?).</p><p>Syed.</p>  </div>
