      <div class="forum-posted-on">
      	  <h6 class="date-posted">Posted</h6>
	      <span class="date-time permalink"><a href="/comment/10406#comment-10406" rel="bookmark">Thu, 03/20/2014 - 15:44</a></span>	
	      	      	        	
	        	
	        	      	    </div>      </div>

    <div class="forum-post-panel-main clearfix">
    
	  <div class="forum-post-info clearfix">	
	    	    	    
	  </div>     
      <div class="forum-post-content">
        <span rel="sioc:reply_of" resource="/developer-resources/forum/developers/alljoyn-firefox-os" class="rdf-meta element-hidden"></span>
  <div class="field-comment-body view-mode-full">
    <p> </p><p>   Thanks Stevek</p><p>   1. Thanks for confirming. Yes, the documentation says that it creates raw TCP connection and not websocket. <a href="https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/API/TCPSocket" rel="nofollow">https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/API/TCPSocket</a></p><p>   2. I was thinking on the lines of accessing Alljoyn daemon using a websocket or HTTP Restful APIs (so we don't have to use TCP socket in javascript) from a user application. Since I am trying to think about different ways to make it work, I am kind of throwing different options, and I am not very confident of what I asked, and probably it doesn't make much sense. </p><p>   3. This is basically not WebIDL but an Alljoyn question. If I rephrase this question, it could be like (not sure how good I can do): What are those essential alljoyn objects that a simple front-end application (lets say 'chat') could directly access, e.g. 'busattachment' is one and does most of the job for the apps. what are others that are necessary?. If there is any document that explains minimal set of objects a simple app needs to implement, it would be helpful and useful starting point.</p><p>Thanks again for your patience.</p>  </div>
      </div>

      
          </div>
  </div> 
